@node 11 "11. AI Docs"

@{b}AI Opponents
============@{ub}
    
	There are currently three different AI opponents available in 
Invasion Force.  These are: AI#2, AI#3, and AI#4 (catchy names, no?). There
used to be an AI#1 as well, but it has been retired, although it will be 
explained in the following section anyway.
	To select a particular AI opponent to be used for a particular 
player (i.e. to make player 3 use AI#4) it must be done when setting up the
parameters for a new game.  Select a player number from the button row
numbered from 1 to 8, then select "Computer" in the choice widget below the
row of buttons - the slider at the bottom left of the window will activate.
Then simply move the slider until it reads the number of the AI opponent
you wish to use (1 to 10).  This only affects the selected player number
though - to make more opponents AI you need to repeat these steps with other
player numbers.
	The slider selections allow up to 10 different AI opponents to be 
selected.  However, only 3 are available, so selecting 1 or 2 will use AI#2,
selecting 3 will use AI#3, and selecting 4 or above will use AI#4.  When
AI#5 is available, then selecting a 4 will use AI#4 and selecting 5 or 
higher will use AI#5.
	So why all the different AIs?  This is an ongoing project and I
wanted to be able to work on newer, better AIs without losing older, but
still working, AIs in the process.  This is a learning experience for me as
well, so the newer AIs use some of the older AIs code (as appropriate). 
Also, should anyone want to pick up the code and improve the AIs they can
start with the basics and learn as I have learned.  Then either improve on
what I have done or take their own approach (but still possibly using some
of the low-level routines I have written, such as path finding, etc.)
	Following are descriptions of each of the 4 current AIs, and a 
preview if you will of AI#5.

AI#1 Description (cyber1.c)
---------------------------
	This was actually the second attempt at an AI for IForce.  The very
first attempt was a "just dive in and make it all happen" approach that
failed miserably - just couldn't get anywhere with it.  So, I took a step
back and made the absolute minimum of an AI - AI#1.
	AI#1 deals only with Infantry units.  It creates then, sets them
off to wander randomly, and has them attack other units or cities when it
finds them.  And if the city is taken, all units return to the city to try
and recapture it.  That's all.
	Well, it worked.  Showed what was missing, and gave me a solid core
of working code to build AI#2 from.

AI#2 Description (cyber2.c)
---------------------------
	This AI deals with Infantry and Armor, and tries to build the one
that is most appropriate to the terrain around the city building it.  The
production is handled by getting requests from all cities owned by that 
AI player and building the highest priority request.  So the city that is
building the unit may not be the one that "owns" it after it is built.
	This gives the cities some measure of cooperation.
	It too just sends units off randomly, but reacts with more 
direction once an enemy city or unit is discovered.  Enemy units near the 
city will be attacked by units of that city (or hunted as I call it, since
it involved both moving towards the enemy units and attacking them). An
enemy or neutral city nearby will be attacked and captured if possible, and
as before, all units of a city will converge on it and try to recapture it
after it has fallen into enemy hands.
	This one can be some fun to play against.  While simple it can 
respond very vigorously to invasion once established.  It throws away it's
random wanderings and hurls wave after wave of Infantry and Armor at an
invader to throw them back into the sea.

AI#3 Description (cyber3.c)
---------------------------
	This AI deals with aircraft as well as Infantry and Armor.
	AI#3 does production a little differently still - it holds a raffle.
Each city puts in its own request for units to be built, each with a 
priority associated with it.  The city doing the production then adds up
all the priorities and rolls a random number to pick what gets produced.  A
higher priority request has a higher probability of being selected, but any
one of the requests can be selected.  Hopefully that randomness makes the
AI a bit harder to predict.
	This also had the original path finding algorithm which could take
inordinate amounts of time to find a path (since it worked recursively). 
This path finding routine has been replaced by one in AI#5 (even though AI#5
is not finished yet, some parts are).
	It includes new commands for moving randomly (more like a billiard
ball than a mexican jumping bean) and searching with aircraft (which is 
based on a lookup table of offsets from the city's location).
	Fighters and bombers are used for exploration, patrolling, and 
defense.  Aircav are only used to attack cities that are detected by are not
accessible by ground forces (Infantry and Armor).
	Still not great, but a start.

AI#4 Description (cyber4.c)
---------------------------
	This AI is a slightly modified version of AI#3 - it does not add
any new unit types to the kinds it uses, but does add a little more to the
overall functionality.
	This AI adds a command to walk the coastline - useful for having 
ground or naval units map the edges of an island or continent - and a new
goto command with some improvements over the older one.
	Not much else.

AI#5 Description (cyber5.c)
---------------------------
	This AI is supposed to be the first foray into a full featured AI
that works with all the unit types - so it adds all the naval units to the
ground and air units that previous AIs use.
	Currently, the unit production selection routines are in written,
as well as the new path finding algorithm.  It is far from finished.
	This new path algorithm implements a full-blown A* (aye-star) 
search, supporting the new roads and terrain types as well as selectable 
speed settings (you can get a bit slower, more exhaustive search, or a 
quicker, less rigorous search).  This algorithm is being used extensively 
for the human player as well as the AI opponents to enable units to "goto" 
another location efficiently.
	Also new here is a "smart" routine to calculate odds in combat of
units vs. other units - taking into account player settings, current unit
damage, terrain types, etc., etc.  Quite complex, it needs to be reworked
to handle the new combat system.



Known Problems with AI Opponents
================================
	In an effort to chase down bugs in the AI code, I added several
checks to try and detect when *bad things* happen (since I can't run
Enforcer).  So, if you see a message that starts:
	"Error! Unit List Fouled..."
	You might as well reboot.  The game cannot exit gracefully as the
system memory pool pointers have gotten corrupted somehow or other.  You
might as well reboot.
	So please save games in progress often.  You can load up a game
saved from previous turns and continue on (unfortunately the problem is
very sporatic - it refuses to repeat itself, otherwise I would have found
it by now).  My hope is that when all Enforcer hitting code has been fixed
this problem will never surface again.
	AI#3 and AI#4 have been reported to "lock up" or take "forever" to
process a turn.  If you can get this to happen with the latest revs, let
me know please.



Bug Report Information for AI Opponents
=======================================
	Since the AI Opponents are a mixed bag of old and new code, there
are a number of items that are needed to pinpoint a problem in the AI 
code.
	1) First is the revision of the program, of course.  If it is not
one of the latest (or *the* latest) I may not be able to help - I don't 
keep development environments very far back at all.
	2) Which AI opponent type (AI#2, AI#3, AI#4) is the player?  The
different opponents act very differently, and use different code.
	3) 
