@node 12 "12. Map Editor"

@{b}Map Editor
==========@{ub}

{Some notes from me, Ed Snyder :) }
    
I figured that I've done enough damage to the map editor now, so it's time
to write some form of docs for it. 

Once entering the map editor the screen will fill with blue hexes (that's
the ocean terrain!). The title bar will change to "Map Editor vX.x" (the
X.x being the current version of the map editor, NOT the game!). Also, in
the title bar you will notice the x/y readout when you move the mouse. This
lets you know which hex the mouse cursor is currently over.

MENUS:
------

Project:

        [L] Load Map - This will load a map file into the map editor.
        
        [S] Save Map - This will save any maps you have created or edited.
        
        [R] Resize Map - This allows you to change the size of the map.
                Just remember, the bigger the map the more memory required.
           
        [C] Clear Map - This will erase the currently displayed map and
                fill the display will the currently selected terrain type.
            
        [X] Exit Map Editor - This will exit the map editor, NOT the 
                entire program. If your map wasn't saved you'll get
                the usual warning. 
        
        [Q] Quit Program - This will quit the entire program and drop you
                back at Workbench (or wherever you came from). Any 
                unsaved maps will result in the usual warning.
                
Terrain:
        
        (Spacebar) Toolbar - This toggles a small window with all of
                the terrain types. From here you can select a terrain
                type and then return to the map window and draw with
                the newly selected terrain. There's also an INFO button
                that will display info on the selected terrain.
                
        Terrain Types - These are the available terrain types. These may
                also be selected from the Toolbar (above).
                
        (I) INFO - This will display info on the selected terrain. This
                option is also available from the toolbar. This is
                explained in more detail below.
                
Other:

        World View - This will shrink your map and display it, in its 
                entirety, in a separate window.
                
        [M] Random Maps - This neat little button will take you to the
                Random Map Generator. This option is explained in more
                detail below.
        
        [I] Statistics - This will display the current map statistics.
                Such as... the percentage of each terrain types, number
                of cities, etc.
                
        =-----------------------------------------------------------------=
        

TOOLBAR:
--------

        Operation of the Toolbar is simple. The spacebar will toggle it
        on(displayed) or off(not displayed). When ON, you may select a
        terrain type simply by clicking on it with the mouse. Once you
        have selected a terrain type you will need to toggle the Toolbar
        OFF in order to draw with it. No drawing is currently possible
        with the Toolbar ON. This may change in the future.
        
        If you happen to have a 3-button mouse you can toggle the Toolbar
        with the MIDDLE mouse button.
        
        Also present are two buttons, OKAY and INFO. Okay just toggles the
        Toolbar back OFF. The Info button is described below.
        
        The close gadget (upper left corner of most Amiga windows) has the
        same effect as the Okay button.
        

INFO:
-----

        The Info window displays more detailed information about the 
        selected terrain. It will show the terrain itself and the name
        of the terrain. Below that it will show all of the unit types.
        Any unit that is crossed out cannot traverse the selected 
        terrain type. 
        
        Below all of that is the movement costs, speed, etc. These
        items were explained earlier in this doc, so I won't bother
        repeating it here.
        

RANDOM MAPS:
------------                 

        The Random Map Generator window is a huge, not so pretty, beast.
        Within it lurks all those things your mother warned you about! :)
        
        Actually, it's just a big window with several sliders and a few
        buttons thrown in for good measure. Across the width of the 
        window is a row of vertical sliders. There's one for each of the
        terrain types. These sliders select the percentage (more or less)
        of each terrain to be generated in the random map. To the far 
        right of these sliders in a small box that displays the current
        total percentage of the map. This cannot be higher than 100%, but
        may be lower. 
        
        NOTE: There is an EXTRA slider displayed, but not currently
              marked or in use. This is for the continents/islands
              option in the next release. 
              
        Also to the right are three buttons. These are HELP!, GENERATE,
        and PRESETS. The HELP! button will display some quick help data.
        The GENERATE button will generate your map, based on the settings
        you've selected. The PRESETS button will allow you to randomly
        generate a preset environment (i.e. Desert). As soon as I complete
        this option I'll describe its use here.
        
        TIPS: Before using the Random Map Generator make sure you have
              set the map size of your choice.
              
              Don't set any ocean, since the ocean terrain is already
              in the blank map. This will help to eliminate that camo-
              netting effect. :)
              
              To CANCEL the generation just click the close gadget.
              
        After the map is generated you will be prompted to select the
        number of cities to be sprinkled. After that is complete you 
        can save your map or hand edit it to fine tune it a bit.


        =-----------------------------------------------------------------=
 

DRAWING MAPS:
-------------

        Drawing a map is fairly simple, but I'll try to explain it a 
        little in detail.
        
        First, make sure the map size is what you want. At the present
        time resizing the map clears the current map from the display,
        so you will need to set your map size BEFORE starting to draw.
        
        After you have sized the map, just toggle the Toolbar and select 
        a terrain (or you can select it from the menu). Then toggle
        the Toolbar to the OFF position and you're ready to draw. Clicking
        on a hex, with the mouse, will cause the terrain you selected
        to be drawn in that hex. If you holding the mouse button (the
        left one) down while moving the mouse then each hex the mouse
        cursor passes over will be filled with the terrain you selected.
        Just repeat this process until you've created your map.
        
        New in this release is the ability to add ROADS to your maps.
        To draw a road simply hold down the control (CTRL) key on the
        keyboard while using the mouse to draw, just as you did with the
        terrain. Roads can be placed on water type terrain to create
        bridges. Roads have some benefits where movement costs are
        concerned.
        
        After you've added the roads you can add in your cities. There
        are some terrains (like the water types) that cities are not
        allowed. If you try to place a city there you will get the
        usual "Oh no you don't!" requester. :) After you've placed your
        cities you can then go back and name them. Just make sure the
        city terrain type is still selected and then click on each
        city in your map. A small window will be displayed asking you
        for the name.
        
        After all that, you're done (more or less). Just save it and 
        you will be able to use it in future games.
        
        TIPS:
                If you just want a map with no particular shape or order
                then use the Random Map Generator to create your basic
                map. Then touch it up by hand to suit your needs.
                
                If you map is to be mostly one terrain type (like
                plains or ocean) then select that terrain type and 
                use the clear map option from the menu. This will
                flood (fill) the map with the selected terrain. Then
                you can just touch it up. This could speed things up
                on a large scale map.
                
                
        =-----------------------------------------------------------------=
         
        That's all I could think of for now. As more features are added
        this doc will be updated. Enjoy!        


@endnode
